\par }\pard\plain \nowidctlpar\widctlpar\adjustright \f1\fs20 {Selects which type of information is to be displayed in the graph.
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s3\sb240\sa60\keepn\nowidctlpar\widctlpar\outlinelevel2\adjustright \shading2500 \b\f1\fs20\cf2 {Bar and Line Graph
\par }\pard\plain \nowidctlpar\widctlpar\adjustright \f1\fs20 {Selects the type of graph to display in the Received and Sent panels.
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s3\sb240\sa60\keepn\nowidctlpar\widctlpar\outlinelevel2\adjustright \shading2500 \b\f1\fs20\cf2 {bps and Bps
\par }\pard\plain \nowidctlpar\widctlpar\adjustright \f1\fs20 {The current and average values reflect data throughput rates using either bits per second or bytes per second.  Throughput is the amount of data that has been s
ent, or received, within a specific duration of time.  The greater the throughput, the faster your Internet connection is.
\par 
\par By convention, data transmission devices, such as modems and networks, are measured in }{\i bits per second}{, or }{\i bps}{.  Data storage devices, such as hard drives and memory, are measured in }{\i bytes}{ and use a capital B as in }{\i 
Bytes per second}{, or }{\i Bps}{.  To avoid confusion, NetPerSec uses the entire word as in Bytes/sec and bits/sec when displaying values.
\par 
\par When viewing data transmission rates in b
its per second (bps), you are comparing the efficiency of your modem or network interface to the actual data throughput of your Internet connection.   For example, if you are using a 56 kbps modem, and want to see how well it is performing, use the bits p
e
r second option in NetPerSec.  Displaying bits per second is also helpful when playing media over the Internet such as streaming video.  If your cable connection is currently averaging about 150 kbps you'll know beforehand that selecting the high bandwidt
h 300 kbps movie will result in long pauses and dropped frames.  You'll get better results with the smaller 100 kbps version.
\par 
\par When displaying bytes per second (Bps), you are measuring efficiency in terms of data storage and the calculations are done using 
binary format.  You will want to use this option when downloading files off of the Internet or moving files across a network.  The values displayed in NetPerSec will be consistent with those reported by your browser, or FTP utility, when indicating the by
tes received per second.
\par 
\par Values may also be combined with the standard metric prefixes: kilo, mega, and giga.  These prefixes are abbreviated using the single letters k,K,M and G.   Please see the }{\uldb\cf11 Bits, Bytes and Metric Prefixes}{\v IDH_bits__bytes__and_the_met
ric_prefixes}{\field{\*\fldinst { macrobutton NextField }}{\fldrslt }}{\field{\*\fldinst {\cf1  }{\cf6 macrobutton DoJump2 <+>}}{\fldrslt }}{\field{\*\fldinst {\cf1  macrobutton NextField }}{\fldrslt }}{\field{\*\fldinst {\cf1  macrobutton NextField }
}{\fldrslt }}{ section for more information.
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s2\sa120\keepn\nowidctlpar\widctlpar\outlinelevel1\adjustright \b\i\f1\cf12 {
\par Comparing NetPerSec's Results with other Utilities
\par }\pard\plain \nowidctlpar\widctlpar\adjustright \f1\fs20 {When comparing the average data throughput reported in NetP
erSec with the results displayed in other utilities, such as your browser, or FTP program, it is very likely that the two throughput rates are different.  The reason for this is because averages are calculated by using the total bytes received, or sent, s
t
arting at a specific point in time and then dividing the amount by the elapsed time.  Since it is unlikely that both NetPerSec and the other utility began at the same exact point in time to base the average calculations on, the numbers that are reported w
i
ll be different.  However, over time, usually within 10 to 15 seconds, the numbers reported from each utility will gradually begin to coincide with each other.  The most accurate method to determine data throughput is to download a large compressed file, 
over 1MB, from a local server, preferably from your own ISP. 
\par 
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s2\sa120\keepn\nowidctlpar\widctlpar\outlinelevel1\adjustright \b\i\f1\cf12 {Modem Connections
\par }\pard\plain \nowidctlpar\widctlpar\adjustright \f1\fs20 {When using a modem connection you may occasionally notice data transmission bursts that exceed the rated speed of your modem.  This is a result of the compression and bufferin
g used with modems and is completely normal.  You will notice that these bursts occur more frequently when viewing Web pages containing lots of text and rarely when downloading files that have already been compressed.  For best results, you should use a }
{\uldb\cf11 sampling rate}{\v IDH_options_tab}{\field{\*\fldinst { macrobutton NextField }}{\fldrslt }}{\field{\*\fldinst {\cf1  }{\cf6 macrobutton DoJump2 <+>}}{\fldrslt }}{\field{\*\fldinst {\cf1  macrobutton NextField }}{\fldrslt }}{\field{\*\fldinst {
\cf1  macrobutton NextField }}{\fldrslt }}{ of one second or higher, and rely on the Average throughput values when evaluating your connection speed.
\par 
