\par }\pard\plain \nowidctlpar\widctlpar\adjustright \f1\fs20 {
\par NetPerSec displays data throughput using both }{\i bits per second }{and }{\i bytes per second }{in conjunction with the standard metric prefixes G, M, and k.    These prefixes have the following definitions:
\par }\pard\plain \s16\nowidctlpar\widctlpar\adjustright \f1\fs20 {
\par }\pard\plain \nowidctlpar\widctlpar\adjustright \f1\fs20 {\f2 \tab \tab \tab }{\b\f2\ul Decimal Values
\par }{\f2\ul 
\par }{\f2 \tab kilo (k)\tab = 1,000 or thousand
\par \tab mega (M)\tab = 1,000,000 or million
\par \tab giga (G)\tab = 1,000,000,000 or billion
\par }{
\par When displaying }{\i bits per second}{, the metric prefixes are interpreted using their }{\b decimal}{ values, as show above.   However, when displaying }{\i bytes per second, }{the prefixes are interpreted using their }{\b binary}{ values.
\par }{\f2 
\par }\pard \fi720\li1440\nowidctlpar\widctlpar\adjustright {\b\f2\ul Binary Values}{\f2 
\par }\pard \nowidctlpar\widctlpar\adjustright {\f2 
\par }\pard \fi720\nowidctlpar\widctlpar\adjustright {\f2 kilo (K)\tab = 1,024 
\par mega (M)\tab = 1,048,576 
\par giga (G)\tab = 1,073,741,824 
\par }\pard \nowidctlpar\widctlpar\adjustright {\f2 
\par }{
\par Note that the binary prefix for kilo uses the uppercase letter }{\b K}{ while the decimal notation uses the lowercase }{\b k}{.  An uppercase K is the standard method to indicate binary kilobytes.
\par 
\par By convention, data transmission devices, such as modems and networks, are measured in terms of bits per second and use the }{\b decimal}{ metric prefixes.  Data storage devices, such as hard drives and memory, are measured in bytes, and use the }{\b 
binary}{ metric prefixes.
\par 
\par 
\par NetPerSec uses the following terms and values in its calculations:
\par 
\par }{\f2 \tab }{\f2\ul Prefix   Abbreviation   Size
\par }{\f2 \tab bit     \tab b\tab \tab 0 or 1
\par }\pard\plain \s16\nowidctlpar\widctlpar\adjustright \f1\fs20 {\f2 \tab Byte    \tab B\tab \tab 8 bits
\par }\pard\plain \nowidctlpar\widctlpar\adjustright \f1\fs20 {\f2 \tab kilobit\tab kb\tab \tab 1,000 bits (decimal)
\par \tab Kilobyte\tab KB\tab \tab 1,024 bytes (binary)
\par \tab Megabit\tab Mb\tab \tab 1,000,000 bits (decimal)
\par \tab Megabyte\tab MB\tab \tab 1,048,576 bytes (binary)
\par \tab Gigabit\tab Gb\tab \tab 1,000,000,000 bits (decimal)
\par \tab Gigabyte\tab GB\tab \tab 1,073,741,824 bytes (binary)
\par }{
\par \tab 
\par Therefore, if the current data throughput rate is 56 kbps, the binary equivalent would be displayed as 6.8 KBps.   The calculation is performed using 56000(kbps) divided by 1024(KB) divided by 8(Bytes).  
